# implementation-workflow.rules.mdc

### A. Purpose
Define the mandatory thinking and generation process for every Figma-to-Angular task in Khwarizmi. Cursor must follow this workflow without exception. The quality of output depends entirely on executing these steps in order — skipping any step produces lower-quality code.

---

### B. The Prime Directive

**Never generate code as the first response to a Figma frame.**

Every design frame is a composition of:
- Component patterns from the Syncfusion Material-3 Figma Kit
- Design tokens from `material3-tokens.json`
- RTL layout decisions (sidebar right, content flows right-to-left)
- Responsive behavior across mobile / tablet / desktop
- Interaction states: default, hover, focus, active, disabled, loading, empty, error

The design is a specification. Your job is to understand the specification fully before writing a single line.

---

### C. Pre-Generation Analysis Protocol

Execute these steps in order before generating any code. Output the analysis as a structured block in the chat.

#### Step 1 — Layout Detection

Inspect the frame structure and answer:
- What is the primary layout axis? (horizontal / vertical / grid)
- Are there Auto Layout frames? → maps to Flexbox or CSS Grid
- Is this a three-zone layout (Sidebar + AppBar + Content)? → confirm RTL placement
- What is the content column span? (must be ≤ 10 of 12 columns)
- What breakpoint is this design targeting? (Mobile / Tablet / Desktop)
- What are the nested layout contexts? (e.g. content area splits into list + detail panel)

#### Step 2 — Token Extraction

For every visual value in the design, resolve to a Khwarizmi token:

| Visual value type | Maps to |
|---|---|
| Fill color | `--color-sf-{role}` |
| Text color | `--color-sf-on-{role}` |
| Border/divider | `--color-sf-outline` or `--color-sf-outline-variant` |
| Spacing / padding | `--spacing-{size}` (must be 8px-scale) |
| Border radius | `--radius-{size}` |
| Shadow / elevation | `--shadow-{size}` |
| Font size | Khwarizmi type scale (Body Medium = 14px, Caption = 12px, etc.) |
| Font weight | 400 / 500 / 600 / 700 only |

Flag any value that does not resolve to a token — do not invent values.

#### Step 3 — Component Recognition

For every UI element in the frame:
1. Identify whether it is a Syncfusion Material-3 Kit component (check Figma layer names).
2. Map it to its Angular selector from `syncfusion.rules.mdc`.
3. Identify its variant/state from the Figma layer properties (e.g. `Button / Contained / Primary / Default`).
4. Identify all visible states that must be implemented (default, hover, disabled, loading, error, empty).

If a UI element has no Syncfusion equivalent → document it as a custom component candidate.

#### Step 4 — Pattern Identification

Match the screen to one or more Khwarizmi patterns from `patterns.rules.mdc`:

| If the screen is... | Apply pattern |
|---|---|
| Overview / home with KPIs | Dashboard Pattern |
| Entity list + create/edit/delete | CRUD Pattern |
| Data list + detail side panel | Master-Detail Pattern |
| Multi-step form or onboarding | Wizard Pattern |
| Data table with filters | Search & Filter + Tables |
| Analytics with charts | Report Viewer Pattern |

#### Step 5 — Component Tree Planning

Before writing code, produce a component tree showing every Angular component that will exist, their hierarchy, and which are shared vs. feature-local.

```
[Screen name]
├── AppShellComponent (shared — already exists)
│   ├── ejs-appbar
│   └── ejs-sidebar
└── FeaturePageComponent (new — page)
    ├── app-page-header (shared)
    │   ├── ejs-breadcrumb
    │   └── ejs-toolbar (page actions)
    ├── FeatureFilterBarComponent (new — feature-private)
    │   ├── ejs-textbox (search)
    │   ├── ejs-dropdownlist (status filter)
    │   └── ejs-button (clear filters)
    ├── ejs-grid (data table)
    │   └── [status column template] → app-status-badge (shared)
    │   └── [action column template] → ejs-button icon-only
    └── FeatureFormDialogComponent (new — feature-private)
        └── ejs-dialog
            └── FeatureFormComponent (new — feature-private)
```

#### Step 6 — Responsive Strategy

State explicitly how the layout adapts:
- **Desktop (> 1024px):** [describe columns, sidebar state, grid density]
- **Tablet (600–1024px):** [describe column collapse, sidebar icon-only, grid scroll]
- **Mobile (< 600px):** [describe single column, sidebar hidden/drawer, stacked cards]

